text: I come from a wrestling family, my dad and my uncle have been wrestling since they were in diapers, and my uncle went to a state championship, my grandpa is also a hardcore wrestler. My cousin and I tried it once for a few months, we were 12 at the time, and we were the only girls there. Everyone else had been wrestling since they could walk, and we had been wrestling for two months. I went to two small tournaments, never won a match, and the second tournament has a rule that if you don't win one of your first two matches, you can't try a third time. I was pretty sure I hated wrestling, I had to wait until the season was over before I could stop. But I can't deny it made me fit, and healthy, I worked hard and I got very strong and flexible by the time I stopped. I almost regret stopping, now I have excess fat and self-confidence issues that I didn't have when I was doing wrestling. It did wonders for my health, but I didn't like it very much. I hardly ever won a match in practice. I remember once, I did something odd instinctively (my dad used to roughhouse with me when I was little and I guess he used some wrestling moves) I did a move that I had seen my dad do all the time and my grandpa was so shocked, he asked me where I had learned how to do that move so perfectly. I was so excited, and also a bit surprised. Once I think I had a nervous breakdown after a match in a tournament. My dad was helping with a different match and I couldn't find him, and I really needed his support for my match, he found me and watched my match, (I lost of course) and after I just started crying so hard, just because I was scared that he wouldn't be there. He took me outside to try to calm me down, and I just sat in the grass sobbing and hyperventilating, covered in sweat and tears, and shaking. Sorry, I went on a HUGE rant there. Anyone else have a similar experience?
